comment: The lawyer, "Lindsay Glazer", is incorrect in her interpretation of Justice Nicol's finding that the allegations against Depp were "substantially true".  This does not mean "more likely than not".  The UK does not follow US civil liability standards.  In fact, Justice Nicol's finding means that he believed that nearly ALL the facts as presented by Heard were true and that the allegations against Depp were likewise nearly ALL true.  This goes much further than "more likely than not".  While not an exact corollary because UK law does not have standards of proof essentially, the closest approximation would be the US standard of "clear and convincing evidence" (a very, very high bar to meet) - but really even beyond this somewhat.  The travesty of the case is that incompetent and highly biased Justice Nicol simply accepted at face value as true essentially everything that Heard claimed while, for the most part, denying that Depp's evidence had any merit.  Justice Nicol, a typical Brit leftist and feminist sympathiser, chose to simply believe Heard without the benefit of any credible supporting evidence whatsoever.  The case shows the contrasts, by the way, between the UK legal system (devoid of individual, fundamental civil rights) versus that of the US legal system (premised upon the notion of individual fundamental rights).

Why not speak to a UK lawyer? Why get someone on who ‚Äúdoesn‚Äôt know‚Äù UK law? I‚Äôm a UK lawyer and UK and American law are vastly different (I‚Äôve studied both up to masters level). 

What she‚Äôs referencing in the beginning is a UK civil law standard ‚Äúbalance of probabilities‚Äù ie which is more likely to be true. People are getting muddled and applying a criminal standard ‚Äúbeyond reasonable doubt‚Äù. 

The S*n simply had to prove, as per UK common law,  that they ‚Äúreasonably believed it was true‚Äù. Reasonably is a word open to massive interpretation. I‚Äôm not surprised by the judgment in the slightest.

Before people pile on I‚Äôm team Depp..

USC 18 ¬ß2382 - Misprision of treason Whoever having knowledge of treason, conceals

USC 18 ¬ß241; CONSPIRACY AGAINST RIGHTS: If two or more persons conspire to

enjoyment of any right they shall be fined under this title or imprisoned not more than ten
years, or both

USC 18 ¬ß242; DEPRIVATION OF RIGHTS UNDER COLOR OF LAW: Whoever,
under color of any law, statute, ordinance, regulation, or custom, willfully subjects any
person in any State the deprivation of any rights shall be fined under this title or imprisoned
not more than one year, or both; 

USC 18 ¬ß2071: Whoever willfully and unlawfully conceals, removes, mutilates, obliterates,
or destroys, or attempts to do so, documents filed or deposited with any clerk or officer of
any court, shall be fined or imprisoned not more than three years, or both

USC 18 ¬ß2076: CLERK IS TO FILE: Whoever, being a clerk willfully refuses or neglects
to make or forward any report, certificate, statement, or document as required by law, shall
be fined under this title or imprisoned not more than one year, or both. 

USC 42 ¬ß1983; CIVIL ACTION FOR DEPRIVATION OF RIGHTS: Every person
who, under color of any statute, ordinance, regulation, custom, or usage, of any State
subjects, or causes to be subjected, any person within the jurisdiction thereof to the
deprivation of any rights, privileges, or immunities secured by the Constitution and laws,
shall be liable to the party injured in an action at law. 

USC 42 1985; CONSPIRACY TO INTERFERE WITH CIVIL RIGHTS: If two or
more persons in any State or Territory conspire for the purpose of depriving, either directly
or indirectly any persons rights the party so injured or deprived may have an action for the
recovery of damages against any one or more of the conspirators.

comment:
Ok so here's the big issue with most of the US based analysis of the case

Truth is an absolute defense to defamation because no person has a right to a reputation they do not deserve. I.e it's not about whether The Sun had enough information to base the claim on; it's about whether or not the claim was true. I'm seeing a lot of commentators saying that the judge found that there was no defamation. That's not true. He found that thestatements were defamatory, but that The Sun was not liable for the damage caused because the defamatory statements were true.

I have serious issues with the judgement as well, as I think the judge was extremely biased, refused to place weight on evidence for frivolous reasons, and applied double standards when it came to what evidence he was willing to accept and from whom. HOWEVER, I believe an appeal by Depp would be unsuccessful because the Court of Appeal is NOT a trier of fact. So long as the judge did not misdirect himself in law (I don't believe he did), and didn't reach a conclusion that no trier of fact could ever reach based on the evidence before him (I don't believe he did this either), the Court of Appeal is not at liberty to substitute its own judgement for the judgement of the judge because he had the benefit of seeing the witnesses and they did not. So what you'll probably see, provided he even gets leave to appeal in the first place, is that while the judges on the Court of Appeal may not share the same opinions as the judge did on the interpretation of the evidence, ultimately the conclusions the judge drew were within the realm of possible conclusions that a finder of fact were entitled to draw to based on the evidence, and thus there is no grounds for appeal.

It's a bad judgement, but it's bad in all the right ways to make it very difficult to appeal.

comment:
Why have you got an American on to discuss this?  It's like getting a plumber to talk about the space program. It does not matter how unreliable Amber Heard might be, it's about is there evidence that at any point he hit her were calling him a wife-beater would be correct. The thing is as well the law is on his side, unlike in the US, the burden is on the publication to prove what they said is true, all Depps team had to do was provide enough doubt on every piece of evidence the publication used which they failed to do. 

The simple fact is if there is a SINGLE situation where he hit her and there is proof and his team can't provide reasonable doubt then the publication are well within their rights to call him a wife beater because he is. It doesn't matter if she hit him thousands of times or if she has lied about some of them.

Oh and seriously, the Sun maybe a tabloid but to label them as the equivalent of The National Enquirer is a joke. Due to the burden in the UK being on the publisher to prove they are correct even the worst tabloids in the UK have a million times more journalistic integrity than even some of the better US publications. They have to cover themselves with things like double independent sourcing (triple sourcing is actually often the norm in the UK) rather than just taking a single source. It's why Celebs rarely take action in the US but will take action against UK papers who pick the story up from a US publication as its winnable in the UK but nigh on impossible in the US to prove its both wrong and that the publication knew it was wrong when printing
